SIMPLE: lucrative
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lucrative
<hw>Lu"cra*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>lucrativus</ets>, fr. <ets>lucrari</ets> to gain, fr.
<ets>lucrum</ets> gain: cf. F. <ets>lucratif</ets>. See
<er>Lucre</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Yielding lucre; gainful; profitable; making increase
of money or goods; <as>as, a <ex>lucrative</ex> business or
office</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The trade of merchandise being the most <qex>lucrative</qex>, may
bear usury at a good rate.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Greedy of gain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such diligence as the most part of our <qex>lucrative</qex>
lawyers do use, in deferring and prolonging of matters and actions from
term to term.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lucratively</ent>⟦br⟧
